A republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers this to be a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In addition, Republican lawyers only identified 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments promulgated new laws from 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon expanded following the November 2010 elections, which included 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced in the year 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo identity card and evidence of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce voting periods in advance, invalidate the right to vote as an elector on the day of the vote and withdraw citizens with a legal record their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indian law.
The republican authorities have endeavoured to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have universal identity cards such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required identity card with pictures.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for democratic candidates, are not allowed in several States to use their identity card with pictures issued by their institutions.
On the other hand, these same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no State required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
However, it turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators sponsored laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on election day in eight States.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, at the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to record approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the enrolment rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other States aimed at reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the voters in the state.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, the whites who made up 76% of the voters represented only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have adopted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make exercising the right to vote more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on and see a clear objective of influencing the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that States that have adopted these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to affirm with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
