Are you also preparing for other "mega events" of this kind in the future?
In May, we will play for the first time in the spring of Prague; here too, we will certainly prepare a quality program with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year at the Czech Republic house in New York and personally, once in the United States, I would like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not so bad that it looks like it's at first.
We have five electric wheelchair members whose gears must travel by lot, of course we also pack a lot of luggage and toolboxes....
Until now everything has been more or less always well done, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, where we have recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to your travel abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of access facilities for people with reduced mobility, the attitude of public opinion towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have your experiences been so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow only in the east is still in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still not accessible to people with disabilities; there it is not common yet that a person moves alone in an electric chair in the center of the city.
They do not yet consider it clear to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association striving to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities is being created.
What do we still need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're still late for...
It is important to mention that improvements and improvements always depend on the efforts of the individuals concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common that people with heavy disabilities move alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilets, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities are actively involved in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather at the forefront of progress!
Respect for the public and access facilities is one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or famous lawyers among us.
For the time being, these are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, so let's go back a few years, what led you to create this group in 1998?
I started working as an educator at Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people willing to invest in something.
