The architects of the MVRDV cabinet prove that the real adventures are not only about imagination. To convince themselves, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected book mountains - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, at last something interesting to see," Lisette Verhaig tells us, a pass on the downside of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computerist in a large neighbouring company, tells us: "Yes, it's really nice, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, iPad and e-books.
Today, no one's doing his own thing in one of these Ranggard libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive at the doors of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls shows the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniature painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to resume their hands on statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the architects' office of Rotterdam MVRDV, master of daring stick diagrams and creator of mind-filled and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with its usual phlegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a scratch on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking, bewildered and wringing their shoulders, Maas, confronting him, stacking his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ending his speech supported by activist arguments by a: "common cry!"
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, or as it is said, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million-euro mountain has cleared the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and some mitoyen buildings and houses for a total of 50 homes.
Early in November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
This is how this small terne village, which so far had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a mayorate of a juicy laideur, whose white facades invite them to think they sheltered a dairy, has enriched a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
True, an elevator carries you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you soak the floor of the building in the discovery of its topography.
The interior is entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant reverberations speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and small boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally, library rays are along the facade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We have completely altered the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been properly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environment centre and the building's technical centre.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambers, sometimes balustrades, sometimes climbing ramps.
A new experience for the view, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the durcis building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, for years the synthetic membrane of a millimetre thickness has been used as substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The membrane finer is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was first compressed in such quantities in plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 metres, the literary café offers us an impressive view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pot ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute mainly to maintaining the ideal level of air moisture in the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project for ecology," Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal temperature.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only gives light to the interior, even to the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across from the glass façade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated stores are responsible for the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computerist, has already risked entering the new library.
Liste Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has helped to fill the gaps in the library which has not yet been fully filled (now it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays overflow everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline that is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new literary history page.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
This is finally a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose abstention at the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status in the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think she doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, however, without being too critical to Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen abstention when voting on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
External policy, such as France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It expresses its willingness to adopt independent positions from those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and abstention at the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important achievements in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to stumble upon public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this because it is not an exclusive unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany interfere with its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are varied.
On the other hand, the United States announced their veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the U.S. domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, of course, the government cannot publicly defend its position.
I believe that the true differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem so.
If you observe relations between Obama and Israel's Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overwhelmed by enthusiasm for Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners?
I think it doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore enter a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will play a role in the future as a locomotive and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This has always been a delicate question.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that marks their independence more.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany want only to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to play a leading role?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulty playing a more important role.
If one looks at, for example, the crisis of the euro, it is noted that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed with a wide range of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only decreasing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this gap, but who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
