The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) was concluded today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Ef tried several times to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the end of the summit, and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian Government's website.
When questioned on the text, they reported that its content had been presented by Peru's president, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
Access of journalists to summit information has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that was circulating among journalists was given by press officers from some of the Unasur governments that were attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some malaise among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media demanding more important information.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech rather than the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd Arab South American Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had not also issued the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgement of the Hague Court which splits a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and stated that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleadings of both parties in the trial that Lima has tried against Santiago and that starts in The Hague on Monday.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we bring before this international court today," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chili has always been, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts," added President Piñera, handing over to President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international court, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former President Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 project lines had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing residence permit agreements".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "co-operation in combating urban insecurity and international organized crime, measures to improve drug accessibility, low-priced Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and see a better future for our populations," said President Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 flagship projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he noted that five were concerned with Peru and were located on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador although it had not given any further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation of Paraguay.
"We hope that the country's electoral process will allow it to be re-entered into the Union of South American Nations", of which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a judgement of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," President Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will call for a discussion with that country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they planned to attend the taking power of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
