Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basket-ball is my whole life"
The “Hetin” Reyes basketball trout has spent more than 60 years of his life in connection with the field and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have knowledge of the history of local basketball as large as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage is condemned to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, BSN, with the Bayamón Vacaros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I wore several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his itinerary out of standards, testify.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, those he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vacaros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"That was my best years, the ones I've most benefited from because I had the chance to participate in eight Vacaros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships that were held from 1971 to 1975.
Then I retired at the 1981 championship, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been leading here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a costly player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it?"
That's how Mincy started, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shots.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another one.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros Championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of Mincy's and his duties in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn't made us play the last game, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've seen?
She's one of the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is that of the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won the gold and put a rattle on the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculin" (Ortiz), there were also the youth (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but she gave us a gold medal and great joy during the pre-olympic tournament of Neuquén in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hurruitiner in place of players suspended by the Imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all predictions.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
Without a doubt, this is Piculin Ortiz.
