A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when Professor of Religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hammock there: the end of the "great count" of the Mayan calendar on 21 December, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what he was expecting in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax guffre that some called the "Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of time thought would trigger the apocalypse.
"I didn't realize that this would be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever met," said Professor Charmé this week to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we said it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the Apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to give courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
At the Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker delivered the course "Media, Culture and End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas thrive with time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of State of Pennsylvania, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an Assistant Professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, if the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students need to study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which does not leave students any choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," Restall said.
The courses have turned out to be quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, University of Rutgers-Camden.
Because the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a question of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursery, says he has seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this matter," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, and even less than one teacher, told us not to believe in the end of the world of December 21.
"Our first project dealt with Maya prophecy, and in a way we discredited it," said Julie Zegle, a senior student in the Temple, aged 21 and originating in West Chester.
The Mayas never predicted the end of the world, this is only a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I agree that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back to centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused an increase in these speculations.
"In other parts of the world, people don't think about it," he says.
This is mostly an Anglophone world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that we were teaching here about "the end of the world".
"The Philippines do not participate in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
